Why It Happens

In popup edit mode, Kendo generates editor fields like this:

<input name="OrigSupplierName_input" id="OrigSupplierName" ...>


or sometimes:

<input data-role="combobox" name="OrigSupplierName_input" />


⚠️ So the real input’s name may not literally be "OrigSupplierName" —
it could be "OrigSupplierName_input", "OrigSupplierName" or even something like "models[0].OrigSupplierName" depending on your model binding.

That’s why your selector:

popup.find("[name='OrigSupplierName']")


doesn’t match anything, resulting in undefined.

✅ The Reliable Fix

Instead of trying to match by name, find the widget by its wrapper class or data-role.

Here’s the robust version that works in all popup modes:

function onSupplierNumChange(e) {
    var combo = e.sender; // The OrigSuppNum ComboBox
    var popup = combo.wrapper.closest(".k-window-content");

    // More tolerant selector: look for any input related to OrigSupplierName
    var supplierNameCombo = popup.find("[data-role='combobox']")
        .filter(function () {
            // Check if its 'name' or 'id' attribute contains OrigSupplierName
            var n = $(this).attr("name") || "";
            var i = $(this).attr("id") || "";
            return n.indexOf("OrigSupplierName") > -1 || i.indexOf("OrigSupplierName") > -1;
        })
        .data("kendoComboBox");

    console.warn("Found OrigSupplierName combo:", supplierNameCombo);

    if (supplierNameCombo) {
        supplierNameCombo.value("");
        supplierNameCombo.text("");
    }

    // Keep your model in sync
    if (window.currentNscPartsModel) {
        currentNscPartsModel.set("OrigSupplierName", "");
    }
}


✅ This version looks at both the name and id attributes,
so it works regardless of how Kendo generates the editor HTML.
